div.p: This document charts the progress made so far in collecting plant samples for the Darwin Tree of Life project. Overall, 356 specimens have been collected up until 28-May-2021. A full and updated list of the DToL plant species, priorities, and collections can be found here for bryophytes, and here for vascular plants.
Fig. 1 - the bar shows the current number of plant families collected, split by vascular plants and bryophytes. The target is 132 for vascular plants, and 128 for bryophytes (red dashes).
Fig. 2 - bar charts split by family, genus, and species which show the number of taxa collected at each taxonomic level.
Fig. 3 - the distribution of genome size variation in collected plants. Genomes greater than 25Gb excluded (5). There is currently a 543-fold variation in genome sizes collected.
Fig. 4 - spike map of Great Britain and Ireland, showing areas where samples have been collected so far. Data drawn from COPO.

Summary charts by Max Brown, Lucia Campos-Dominguez, and Alex Twyford. Plant collections were made by Maarten Christenhusz at the Royal Botanic Garden Kew, David Bell and Markus Ruhsam at the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh, and by Darwin Tree of Life collaborators around Britain and Ireland. Genome size estimates were generated by Sahr Mian and Ilia Leitch at the Royal Botanical Gardens, Kew.
